SQL JOINs

SQL JOINs are used when you need data across multiple related tables.

Database Relationships and SQL JOINs

Lets say we wanted to list each product name along with its product category name. Since onle the ID of the product category exists in the product table, and the product categorys name is in the product_category table, we have to combine the data in the product and product_category tables together in order to generate this list. Each product can only belong to one category, but each category can contain many products, so this is a one-to-many relationship. The primary key in the product_category table is the product_category_id. There is also a product_category_id in each row of the product table that serves as a foreign key, identifying which category each product belongs to.

LEFT JOIN

The LEFT JOIN pulls all records from the table on the left side of the JOIN, and only the matching records from the table on the right side of the join.

The syntax for creating a LEFT JOIN is:
SELECT [columns to return]

FROM [left table]

[JOIN TYPE][right table]

ON [left table].[field in left table to match]=[right.table].[field in right table to match]

To pull a list of all products with each products category name listed, we make the product table the left table in the query by listing it first after FROM, and the product_category table the right side by listing it after the LEFT JOIN, and well match up the records using the product_category_id fields.

SHOW databases
USE farmers_market
SELECT * FROM farmers_market.product
  LEFT JOIN product_category
  ON product.product_category_id = product_category.product_category_id

This query asks SQL to select all columns and rows from the product table, and all columns from the product_category table for rows where the product_categorys product_category_id matches a products product_category_id.

If we want to return specific columns from the merged dataset, we have to specify which table each column is from, since its possible to have identically named columns in different tables.

SELECT
  product.product_id,
  product.product_name,
  product.product_category_id AS product_prod_cat_id,
  product_category.product_category_id AS category_prod_cat_id,
  product_category.product_category_name
FROM product
  LEFT JOIN product_category
  ON product.product_category_id = product_category.product_category_id

You can create table aliases like this:

SELECT 
  p.product_id,
  p.product_name,
  pc.product_category_id,
  pc.product_category_name
FROM farmers_market.product AS p
  LEFT JOIN product_category AS pc
  ON p.product_category_id = pc.product_category_id
ORDER BY pc.product_category_name, p.product_name

Sometimes JOINs can produce NULL values.

SELECT *
FROM farmers_market.customer AS c
LEFT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
WHERE customer_first_name = "Betty"

This happened because there are some customers without any purchases. We can use a WHERE clause to filter the list to only customers with no purchases:

SELECT c.*
FROM customer AS c
LEFT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
WHERE cp.customer_id IS NULL

The c.* only selects columns from the customer table.

RIGHT JOIN

In a RIGHT JOIN, all of the rows from the right table are returned, along with only the matching rows from the left table, using the fields specified in the ON part of the query. An example of when we would use a RIGHT JOIN would be if we wanted to list all product categories and the products in each, and you dont care about products that were not put into a category, but you did care about categories that didnt contain any products.

We can use a RIGHT JOIN to list all purchases and the customers associated with them by pulling all records from the customer_purchases table, and only customers from the customer table with a purchase.

SELECT *
FROM customer AS c
RIGHT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id

INNER JOIN

An INNER JOIN only returns records that have matches in both tables.

Inner Join

A Common Pitfall when Filtering Joined Data

If you filter for values on the right side when doing a left join, the result will be an INNER JOIN.

Lets say we want to write a query that returns a list of all customers who did not make a purchase at the March 2, 2019, farmers market. We will use a LEFT JOIN, since we want to include the customers who have never made a purchase at any farmers market, so wouldnt have any records in the customer_purchases table:

SELECT c.*, cp.market_date
FROM customer AS c
LEFT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
WHERE cp.market_date <> "2019-04-02"

This query is problematic because the result is missing customers who have never made a purchase. This happened because we filtered the market_date in the customer_purchases table, which is on the right side of the JOIN.

One solution that will allow us to filter the results returned using a field in the table on the right side of the join while still returning records that only exist in the left side table is to write the WHERE clause to allow NULL values in the field:

SELECT c.*, cp.market_date
FROM customer AS c
LEFT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
WHERE (cp.market_date <> "2019-04-02" OR cp.market_date IS NULL)

The second problem is that the output contains one row per customer per item purchased, because the customer_purchases table has a record for each item purchased, when we just wanted a list of customers. We can solve this by removing the market_date field from the customer_purchases side of the relationship, so the purchase dates arent displayed, then using the DISTINCT keyword, which removes duplicates records in the output.

SELECT DISTINCT c.*
FROM customer AS c
LEFT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
WHERE (cp.market_date <> "2019-04-02" OR cp.market_date IS NULL)

JOINs with More than Two Tables

Lets say we want details about all farmers market booths, as well as every vendor booth assignment for every market date. Perhaps were building an interactive report that lets us filter to a booth, a vendor, or a date, to see the resulting list of booth assignments with additional both and vendor details. To do this we need to join three tables.

We can LEFT JOIN the vendor_booth_assignments to booth, therefore including all of the booths, and LEFT JOIN vendor to vendor_booth_assignments in the results.

SELECT
  b.booth_number,
  b.booth_type,
  vba.market_date,
  v.vendor_id,
  v.vendor_name,
  v.vendor_type
FROM booth AS b
  LEFT JOIN vendor_booth_assignments AS vba ON b.booth_number = vba.booth_number
  LEFT JOIN vendor AS v ON v.vendor_id = vba.vendor_id
ORDER BY b.booth_number, vba.market_date

Exercises Using the Included Database

  1. Write a query that INNER JOINs the vendor table to the vendor_booth_assignments table on the vendor_id field they both have in common, and sorts the results by vendor_name, then market_date.
```sql
SELECT * 
FROM farmers_market.vendor AS v
  INNER JOIN vendor_booth_assignments AS vba ON v.vendor_id = vba.vendor_id
ORDER BY vendor_name, market_date
```

  1. Is it possible to write a query that produces an output identical to the output of the following query, but using a LEFT JOIN instead of a RIGHT JOIN?
```r
SELECT *
FROM customer AS c
RIGHT JOIN customer_purchases AS cp
  ON c.customer_id = cp.customer_id
```
```sql
SELECT *
FROM customer_purchases AS cp
LEFT JOIN customer AS c
  ON cp.customer_id = c.customer_id
```

At the beginning of this chapter, the analytical question When is each type of fresh fruit or vegetable in season locally? was asked, and it was explained that the answer requires data from the product_category table, the product table, and the vendor_inventory table.
